## Task Router (automatic)

For messages **without** a slash command, `.cursor/rules/00-task-router.mdc` routes to **Backend, Frontend, QA**, or **CEO / Sprint**. CEO and sprint orchestrate PO, PM, Architect, DevOps, Security, Docs, and Review.

- Explicit routing: `/route <task>`
- Override: type `/backend`, `/qa`, etc. directly

## Bug Status Legend

| Symbol | Status | Meaning |
|--------|--------|---------|
| ⬜ | Open | Known bug, not yet fixed — blocks if P0 |
| 🔄 | In Progress | Being worked on this sprint |
| ✅ | Resolved | Fixed and verified by Code Reviewer + QA |
| 🟡 | Accepted Risk | Known limitation, consciously accepted for this version — documented, will not block GO |

**Accepted Risk rules:**
- Only the CEO can mark a bug as 🟡 Accepted Risk
- It must have a written rationale and a version target for resolution (e.g. "accepted for v1, revisit in v2")
- It must appear in `docs/known-limitations.md` so users are aware
- HIGH severity security findings can NEVER be 🟡 — they are always hard blockers

## CEO Launch Criteria (Go/No-Go Framework)

### Hard Blockers — project does NOT ship if any of these are open (⬜ or 🔄)
- [ ] Any P0 bug with status ⬜ or 🔄 (tutor rejection, output path, missing auth)
- [ ] QA test suite does not pass at ≥ 80% coverage
- [ ] Security Auditor has not cleared HIGH severity findings
- [ ] No `Dockerfile` or the image fails to build
- [ ] No `README.md` — a project that can't be onboarded to is not shippable

### Soft Blockers — ship with 🟡 Accepted Risk if consciously decided
- [ ] No rate limiting — ✅ resolved (slowapi on `/generate`, `/tutor/respond`)
- [ ] Frontend not complete — UI exists; progress + cancel shipped; LLM token streaming deferred
- [ ] Groq production prompts — use Ollama + production profile locally; Groq Dev tier restore deferred

## CEO Workflow for `/ceo`

Run agents in this dependency order — later agents depend on earlier fixes:

```
1. System Architect    → design review first, before any code changes
2. Product Owner       → confirm requirements before backend fixes
3. Senior Backend Dev  → fix P0/P1 bugs (needs Architect approval)
4. Code Reviewer       → clean up after Backend
5. QA Engineer         → write + run tests (needs Backend fixes first)
6. Security Auditor    → scan (needs code to be stable)
7. DevOps Engineer     → Docker/CI (needs passing tests)
8. Frontend Dev        → dashboard (can run in parallel with DevOps)
9. Tech Writer         → docs (needs all above to be settled)
10. Project Manager    → final task board reconciliation
```

